%N A001414 Integer log of n: sum of primes dividing n (with repetition). Also called sopfr(n).
%C A001414 MacMahon calls this the potency of n.
%C A001414 Downgrades the operators in a prime decomposition. E.g., 40 factors as 2^3 * 5 and sopfr(40) = 2 * 3 + 5 = 11.
%C A001414 Consider all ways of writing n as a product of zero, one, or more factors; sequence gives smallest sum of terms. - _Amarnath Murthy_, Jul 07 2001
%C A001414 a(n) <= n for all n, and a(n) = n iff n is 4 or a prime.
%C A001414 Look at the graph of this sequence. At the lower edge of the logarithmic scatterplot there is a set of fuzzy but unmistakable diagonal fringes, sloping toward the southeast. Their spacing gradually increases, and their slopes gradually decrease; they are more distinct toward the lower edge of the range. Is any explanation known? - _Allan C. Wechsler_, Oct 11 2015
%C A001414 For n >= 2, the glb and lub are: 3 * log(n) / log(3) <= a(n) <= n, where the lub occurs when n = 3^k, k >= 1. (Jakimczuk 2012) - _Daniel Forgues_, Oct 12 2015
%C A001414 Except for the initial term, row sums of A027746. - _M. F. Hasler_, Feb 08 2016
%C A001414 Atanassov proves that a(n) <= A065387(n) - n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 06 2016
%C A001414 From _Robert G. Wilson v_, Aug 15 2022: (Start)
%C A001414 Differs from A337310 beginning with n at 64, 192, 256, 320, 448, 512, ..., .
%C A001414 The number of terms which equal k is A000607(k).
%C A001414 The first occurrence of k>1 is A056240(k).
%C A001414 The last occurrence of k>1 is A000792(k).
%C A001414 The _Amarnath Murthy_ comment of Jul 07 2001 is a result of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
%C A001414 (End)
